title: THE ARTERIAL SUPPLY TO THE ADULT CERVICAL VERTEBRAL BODIES
container-title: The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. British volume
items.abstract: <jats:p> 1. The spinal branches of the vertebral artery were injected with a suspension of barium sulphate and the blood supply of the vertebral bodies of the lower four or five cervical vertebrae investigated radiologically. </jats:p><jats:p> 2. Beneath the posterior longitudinal ligament there is a free dorsal arterial plexus from which a large branch arises to enter the back of the vertebral body. This vessel terminates abruptly at the centre of the body where numerous, much smaller, branches radiate towards the upper and lower surfaces. </jats:p><jats:p> 3. The possible significance of the form of the intravertebral arteries is considered in relation to embolic lesion in vertebral bodies. </jats:p>

title: THE BLOOD SUPPLY OF DEVELOPING LONG BONES WITH SPECIAL REFERENCE TO THE METAPHYSES
container-title: The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. British volume
items.abstract: <jats:p> 1. Periosteal bone is supplied by periosteal vessels and endochondral bone by the nutrient artery. </jats:p><jats:p> 2. In the earliest stages of development the metaphysis is supplied by vessels derived only from the nutrient artery. Later, metaphysial arteries derived from the periosteum take over the supply of its peripheral part, the extent of their area of supply progressively increasing. </jats:p><jats:p> 3. In injected specimens the blood vessels approaching the epiphysial cartilaginous plate end in saccular dilations. Histological sections show these dilations to be blood-filled cartilage lacunae, with no endothelial lining and into which open the blood vessels approaching the epiphysial plate. </jats:p>
